M. iii. 163) the following verse— Luna decus mundi, magni pars maxima caeli, which is certainly from Manilius V. 12- Hinc uocat Orion, magni pars maxima caeli.

In the age of Constantine we can point to one writer who knew and used Manilius, the author of the Latin treatise on Astrology, Julius Firmicus. Scaliger has collected the passages in this work which are modelled on Manilius' poem, and more recently Bechert has cited the most remarkable of them de emend. Manil. p. 18. Two of them bear traces of a very close imitation. Man. V. 61 sqq.
